I'm gonNA write about it

Editor in chief | Yang Jiamin

With the confirmation last Friday (February 21,2020) of Italy's first indigenous case of new pneumonia, i was suddenly in the middle of the "epidemic zone" : 20 Km away at Vo'euganeo, two elderly patients who had tested positive for nucleic acid after several days in hospital, affecting medical care and other patients, and 450 patients and staff inside when the hospital was closed. Each day brought new cases closer to Padova, where I live: As of the evening of the 27th, 116 nucleic acid tests had been positive across the Veneto, including 63 asymptomatic infections, 28 hospitalizations for pneumonia, and eight in critical condition. Twenty were put under medical observation and three were discharged.

Italy is not defenseless in this case: at the national level, it is the first country to announce the closure of a Chinese route since the outbreak of new pneumonia in Wuhan. In daily life, at the end of January 2020, all Chinese returning from China were required to report to the Health Bureau and were quarantined at home for 14 days. More than 200 Chinese in Padova took the initiative to undergo nucleic acid testing and were all negative.

So when I saw the breaking news and the trajectory of patient 1's life, it was like a museum equipped with state-of-the-art security, but was burned to the ground by one of the staff cigarette butts. The virus has good reason to like the Italians, they are warm and outgoing, greeting greeting each other face-to-face (cheeks close to each other three times) , rich and colorful amateur life, there are old and young still can eat every week, play football, run a marathon. So patient 1 single handedly quarantined or medically observed 50,000 people, successfully spread the virus across northern Italy, and followed in the footsteps of Italian tourists across Europe in an unstoppable fashion.

When a small town is diagnosed and all eight Chinese residents are required to undergo a nucleic acid test (all negative) , the Chinese in Italy are by far the safest group to live in -- At least I think so. Our epidemic prevention work began long before the city of Wuhan was shut down.

When I saw the news of the new pneumonia in late January, I became anxious and bought masks from Taobao for my family in China. While the Chinese in Italy are actively raising supplies for the country, I have canceled and postponed overnight my travel photo shoots and overseas weddings during the Spring Festival, caught a few boxes of fish off the grid on Amazon and professional websites, and went to a Chinese supermarket to stock up on two weeks'worth of snacks and spices, self-consciously start the mode of anti-epidemic at home. When the Chinese community is gun-shy, the Italians are very optimistic and confident. In addition to Amazon face masks doubled in price, professional medical website face masks out of stock, locals only think this is the Far East is experiencing a cold.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The author's anti-epidemic supplies include various disinfectants, commonly used drugs, disposable rubber gloves, nasal wash, alcohol-free hand wash, disinfectant wipes and masks. (Chen Baibai / photo)

I began to wear a mask in public places after the Spring Festival. Familiar Italians are wary: In local public health guidelines, masks are worn only by people with severe immunodeficiency or sexually transmitted diseases, which in either case are signs of imminent death. To avoid trouble, I say I'm allergic to pollen, even though the pollen season usually starts in March. The strange Italians, seeing me as a plague, spring away from me. Friends began to have a variety of rumors, true or false hypothesis is the Italian "mask Chinese" discrimination and even violence.

When two cases of Chinese tourists were diagnosed in Italy, the Chinese and the restaurants and businesses they ran became "plague areas" that Italians shunned, and traffic plummeted by 50-80 percent, in Milan, lawmakers go to Chinatown Chinese restaurant to "support Chinese anti-discrimination" . No one could have predicted that three weeks later Chinese businesses would close their doors for fear of being infected by Italians.

There are a lot of international events in Italy in February, the closest to me being Milan Fashion Week and the Venice carnival. Our job at fashion week was predictably cancelled because 80 per cent of Chinese buyers and runway guests failed to show up. Sales of luxury goods in Italy will face a 30 percent drop this year due to the China outbreak, according to ANSA. The tourist market is especially cold: without the flow of tourists during the Spring Festival holiday, the prices of luxury hotels in Venice are nearly halved. But all this does not affect the local song and dance day-to-day, on the new crown pneumonia epidemic, the most important measure is only "look good on the Chinese. ". A widely circulated photo on Chinese social media of a man wearing a protective suit but not the correct face mask was actually a caricature of the epidemic by tourists at the Piazza San Marco.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The image, which has been widely circulated on Chinese websites, is actually a parody of the Venice carnival. (chart / Photo of southern weekend)

Life remained calm in mid-february, although the situation seemed to have eased after the gauntlet that greeted me. By the time the suits were sent back to China, postal workers had become familiar with the procedures and documents, reassuring me that they would be sent out today and expressing sympathy for China's difficulties. I also sent back four boxes of masks I had hoarded, optimistic that Italy would be able to hand in full marks as long as the Chinese community did not have an outbreak.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The author on February 14 and friends together with the donation of protective clothing, but due to the cancellation of direct flights, has not yet arrived in China. (Cham Pak / Photo)

Yet life is always a slap in the face after a rash decision. While EMS was still out at sea, this Italian outbreak broke out. On Friday night, February 21st, when the first locally transmitted cases were announced in Italy, two cities in the north became sick and my circle of friends exploded. The whole page of the Ansha News Agency's website was full of rare reports of the epidemic. The figures went up every hour. I immediately cancelled my trip to Milan the next day to see the venue. I also persuaded the bride who was to come from Cambridge to Venice in early March to be interviewed, by the time you search Amazon's website for "face masks, " all your previous purchases have sold out, and the number of disposable surgical masks has shot up to 100 Euro 50. Think of the past month wearing a new mask every day, for their profligacy feel sorry. A 50 euro box was hastily found, and the next day it was found to be two thin layers: looters are everywhere, which is very similar to the virus.

Friday was a thrilling night in the throbbing numbers. Family and friends sent messages in the early hours of the morning asking how it was going to be in Florida as the outbreak spread across China on Saturday morning. My mother was anxious, and I calmed down after the first few hours: The rapid increase in the number of large areas of surveillance, screening area, information transparency. What's more, the subjects of the tests were close contacts, most of whom had no symptoms and required no treatment. The positive cases were quarantined in time to prevent the spread of the disease.

I experienced the Wenchuan County earthquake in Sichuan and have a strong sense of disaster prevention. So getting out of bed on a Saturday is a top priority: stock up on supplies and prepare for home quarantine. Overnight, 10 life rules have been posted on billboards on city streets, explaining the symptoms of a new coronavirus infection, stressing not to go to the emergency room on your own, wash your hands frequently, and so on, efficiency is something I haven't seen in Italy in 10 years: it used to be impossible to get Italians to work weekends. Article 8 states that goods and packages from China are safe and do not require a nucleic acid test because they have been exposed to them. Article 7 stressed that "only the occurrence of related symptoms or close contact with new pneumonia patients need to wear a mask, daily wearing a mask is not right. ". But the lesson from China is that the new crown is Virus latency, especially in Italy, where the burden of asymptomatic carriers is so great that it is not hard to choose between "not panicking" and "protecting one's self from the other. ".

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The weather is fine, but there are few people

Between guiding policy and independent thinking, Italians also vote with their feet: early Saturday morning DIY home improvement shops sold out of industrial respirators. Goggles and latex gloves are also out of stock, probably a lot of well-informed people read the Chinese news. Wearing a mask, I cut to the chase and stopped loitering. I got what I needed to get to the cash register in five minutes, "Why is she wearing a mask? " "I don't know, maybe it's because she's sick. " Such remarks are considered discriminatory in normal times, should have gone to their manager to complain. But right now I'm just thinking about the snail noodles in Chinese supermarkets, and I'm not in the mood to fight.

China's supermarkets have been largely empty since the outbreak. Italians do not dare to go, nor do Chinese who fear having a domestic carrier visit. But this Saturday is different. The day after the outbreak was announced in Italy, the instant noodles shelves were nearly empty, frozen dumplings were sold out, and there was only one bag of rice left. It seemed that the Chinese in the city, like me, were planning to learn from China how to suffocate a virus at home. The usual shopping spree is over, and everyone is wearing masks to add to the shopping cart, because the boss said that tomorrow no longer open for business, only accept online booking, regular pick-up.

Italian supermarkets are a different story. At least my city isn't being pillaged and emptied, as the Internet seems to suggest. Even in the "yellow zone" of the outbreak: unsealed but tightly controlled areas, including the cities of Milan and Padova, vegetables, meat and even seafood are available, but alcohol hand sanitizers and supplies are out of stock. But this is only the second day of the outbreak, and most Italians who do not know or care about it have no protection and may not be able to get it anytime soon.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Supermarkets are open as usual, with adequate supplies of fruits and vegetables at reasonable prices. (Cham Pak / Photo)

The atmosphere in the city became tense on Saturday afternoon, perhaps because the number of confirmed cases was growing too fast, perhaps because there were too many cases around our city, and others on the streets were wearing masks. The pharmacy downstairs posted a notice saying "masks sold out" at noon. Now, official guidelines in Italy do not recommend that people wear masks on a daily basis, in part out of desperation. After all, limited medical resources can only be used where they are most needed in order to maximize the benefits.

When I came home in the evening, I met the landlord. He was over 70 years old. He had a major operation last year. He was very weak. Now he needed to go to the hospital every week. He covered his nose and mouth with his scarf, hoping to buy two face masks at the drugstore in case of an emergency: it was clearly an impossible task. So I hurried home, grabbed 10 masks from the last box, and sent them downstairs with a bottle of alcohol hand sanitizer. The landlady was as talkative as ever, from my cat and dog to my family back home, and railed about the Italian government's lack of prevention: some citizens asked the health ministry what to do if they were stranded in China, and the health ministry suggested connecting from Thailand to Italy; It also said that the new coronavirus's serious illness is mainly the old people, but the media only emphasized the mild illness mainly can heal itself, as if has ignored the old people's benefit. We stood in the door and outside the chat for a long time, parting time did not as before, she blew a kiss to me, I hand to her, and then we go home, may not see each other for a long time.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The Italians finally put on their masks

Within 48 hours of the outbreak, Italy ordered the closure of the city and the closure of schools, followed by the closure of the Cathedral in Milan, the early closure of the Carnival in Venice, and the cancellation of the Armani press conference for all spectators, leaving only the models to walk the runway. Chinese owners agreed to voluntarily close their shops, bars and barbershops... and put up "a week off" signs. Bosses who have been mocked by the Italian media as "consistently making money on New Year's Eve" have had a long holiday.

Also excited about the holidays are the children who have been suspended from school. Veneto closed schools this week, but did not order home quarantine. Looking out the window at the children playing football in twos and threes, I was torn by the memory of the Italian uncle in the supermarket wearing disposable rubber gloves and buying the last bottle of disinfectant. Italy will need to be very careful to find a balance between individual freedoms and collective interests that can gradually bring the epidemic under control, or, in the next two weeks, will prove whether such a balance exists.

Thursday's new confirmed cases were a little closer to me, this time in downtown Padova. A doctor in a nearby city who treated the dead patient received a positive nucleic acid test after two days of self-isolation. My mother, who was thousands of miles away, was nervous, but I still wore a mask and walked my dog, and life went on as usual. After all, we are no longer learning from scratch. Veneto had 900 beds by the time only 30 cases were diagnosed, and a separate tent shelter was in place to meet quarantine conditions. After a couple of false starts and a trip to Rashomon, a friend in the states sent me two boxes of N95s, and I was reassured by the delivery tracking record.
